  <bioghist id="aspace_468f9fa3344a5ea6fedf1a86a3bb2f98">
    <head>Historical/Biographical Note</head>
<p>Joan Roelofs was Professor of Political Science at Keene State College from 1979 until 2012 specializing in green public adminsitration, the political power of foundations and the ideas of pre-Marxist socialist Charles Fourier. She is the author of <title render="italic">Greening Cities: Building Just</title>, <title render="italic">Sustainable Communities</title>, and <title render="italic">Foundations and Public Policy</title>. She is also a practitioner of book arts.</p>  </bioghist>
  <prefercite id="aspace_dfa0a79ec53de80ed11153069cc4b672">
    <head>Preferred Citation</head>
<p>Identification of item, date; Joan Roelofs Collection on the Green Movement; TAM 651; box number; folder number; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, New York University.</p>  </prefercite>
  <processinfo id="aspace_d5aa097611c66d86115820250b1a2f1b">
    <head>Processing Information</head>
<p>At the time of accessioning, materials were housed in acid-free folders and boxes, and a collection-level record was created. No physical arrangement was performed.</p>  </processinfo>
  <scopecontent id="aspace_1af0b32ff2fcc35e8052a8c5583ae21e">
    <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
<p>This collection consists of various papers, articles, notes and flyers regarding the environment, labor issues and the socio-political situation in America during the late-20th century; as well as issues of numerous publications examining contemporary issues in climate change, environmental politics, and energy policy and development. The collection includes multiple issues of <title render="italic">Green Politics</title> and <title render="italic">Synthesis/Regeneration</title>.</p>  </scopecontent>
